Pretty much. Javascript has the same scoping rules for functions used as expressions:<p><pre><code>    var f = function fac(n) { if (n==0) { return 1; } else {return fac(n-1)*n; } };
    console.log(f(3));
    console.log(fac(3));
</code></pre>
This will log &#x27;6&#x27; and error out on the last one (fac is undefined). This is the same scoping Erlang uses for anonymous function names as far as I can tell, with one difference: Erlang&#x27;s function name is a variable that can be used as such internally. In Javascript, the function name doesn&#x27;t refer to a variable per se:<p><pre><code>    var f = function fac() { console.log(fac) };
    console.log(f);
    f();
</code></pre>
Which will log &#x27;fac()&#x27; and &#x27;undefined&#x27;. In Erlang:<p><pre><code>    1> F = fun Fac() -> Fac end.
    #Fun<erl_eval.44.71889879>
    2> F().
    #Fun<erl_eval.44.71889879>
 </code></pre>
Both instances (F and Fac within the right scope) return the same anonymous function.

